RxWeb - Web Development Using Retro
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This is an attempt to develop a framework for building small
websites and applications using Retro.

Requirements:

 - Linux, BSD, or MacOS X
 - Perl (to run the www-server)
 - Make (for building)
 - Retro (console implementation. -nocurses recommended.
          Use Mat's extended-ngaro for better performance)

Features:

 - Pages are stored in the image
 - Syntax is clean
 - Use any Retro words or constructs
 - Word names = page names


Want to help? Here's some stuff that needs to be done:

 - Better support for embedding stylesheets, scripts
 - Optionally escape output automatically:
   &  ->  &amp;
   "  ->  &quot;
   <  ->  &lt;
   >  ->  &gt;
   and so on...
 - TEST!!!! (and report bugs)
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
A simple example:

: /
 ( html
   ( head ( title ." Demo Page" ) )
   ( body
     ( h1 ." Welcome to Retro" )
     ( p ." This is a test of the WWW package." )
   )
 )
;
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
The syntax is lispy, and is derived from Stefan's old retroweb
system.

Links:

You can use two forms for links:

1) Using the core markup parser

  attr: href='url' ( a .... )

2) Using the concise format

   [a URL ...code/description... ]

E.g., these generate the same HTML:

  attr: href='google.com' ( a ." Click me to go to google!" )
  [a google.com ." Click me to go to google!" ]

Properties:

  id: name
  ( element ..... )

  class: name
  ( element ..... )

  attr: ....
  ( element ..... )

When using properties, you can not have spaces in the line.

CSS:

  css: URL

Scripts:

  script: URL
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
